article.description: Shanna Zolman scored a career-high 28 points and Tennessee made 40-of-46 free throws to hold off Florida 91-82 in overtime.
article.headline: Tennessee gets 41st straight SEC win
article.linkText: Lady Vols use 40 free throws to beat Florida
article.story:
GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Something about Florida brings out the best in Shanna Zolman.

It was a good thing for fifth-ranked Tennessee, which needed every one of her clutch shots to beat the Gators on Thursday night.

A year after scoring a then-career best 23 points against Florida, Zolman established a new high with 28 as the Lady Vols (17-3, 7-0 Southeastern Conference) extended their regular-season league winning streak to 41 games by holding off the Gators 91-82 in overtime.

Zolman went 8-of-9 from the field and 9-of-10 from the foul line, including two free throws with 21.4 seconds left in regulation to tie it at 69.

"I felt like I was shooting in the ocean," Zolman said. "Whenever I have that feeling, I know when I get open looks, it's going to go in."

Florida (12-9, 3-5), which had lost 11 straight to Tennessee by an average of 23.5 points, came within one shot of beating the Lady Vols for only the second time in 35 meetings. Bernice Mosby scored a season-high 28 points for the Gators, but her leaner at the end of regulation bounced off the back of the rim.

Tennessee led all the way in overtime. Sidney Spencer converted a three-point play, including her only field goal of the game, to make the score 72-69, and Zolman followed with a 3-pointer to put the Lady Vols ahead 75-71.

Tennessee then sealed the win by making 12-of-14 free throws to finish 40-of-46 from the foul line, matching its largest lead of the night with the final margin.

Zolman's last two foul shots in regulation were the most important after Danielle Santos gave Florida a 69-67 lead on two free throws with 33.9 seconds left. After a timeout, Zolman drove to the basket on a set play and drew a foul from Mosby, who thought she had a clean block.

Zolman, an 86 percent free-throw shooter entering the game, calmly sank both.

"No one panicked, and Shanna made a big play," Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said. "As she got ready to shoot those two free throws, I said I would bet my house that both of them were going to go in. I didn't have any takers."

Nicky Anosike added 12 points and Spencer had 11 for Tennessee, which won even though leading scorer Shyra Ely had only two points, zero rebounds and four turnovers.

Zolman, a junior guard, came off the bench to play 34 minutes, including all but one minute of the second half and overtime.

Tamia Williams scored 14 for the Gators.

The first half was virtually even in every category, an indication of things to come. Both teams made 10 field goals and 11 free throws, with Tennessee hitting two more 3s to lead 34-32 at the break.
